Title: Markdown Demo
------------------------------------

# Live Markdown demos (`markdown-demo`)

Almost every page in this manual shows a snippet of JMarkdown source beside the
output it produces. Those side-by-side panels are not screenshots and they are
not maintained by hand. They are generated by a single container directive,
`markdown-demo`, that takes one block of source, displays it *and* renders it,
and lays the two results out next to each other.

The point is **a single source of truth**. You write the example once; the demo
shows the literal source on the left and runs that exact same source to produce
the output on the right. The two can never drift apart, because there is only one
copy. When you change the example, both panels change together. This is the same
discipline JMarkdown applies to a whole book — one source, two outputs — applied
in miniature to a documentation snippet.

`markdown-demo` is a container directive. If the container syntax (the
colon-delimited fences) is new to you, read [Directives](directives-syntax.html)
first; this page assumes you know what a container directive is and concentrates
on what is special about this one.

## A first demo

Place your example between an opening fence naming the directive and a matching
closing fence, exactly as you would for any container directive:

```markdown
:::markdown-demo
:span[This is a coloured span.]{.goldenrod}

1. A list *containing markdown code*
2. Isn't that /cool/?
   a. A sublist item with math $\alpha + \beta$.
   b. Another sublist item.
3. So there you are.
:::
```

That produces the panel below. The left pane is the source, syntax-highlighted;
the right pane is what JMarkdown makes of it:

:::markdown-demo
:span[This is a coloured span.]{.goldenrod}

1. A list *containing markdown code*
2. Isn't that /cool/?
   a. A sublist item with math $\alpha + \beta$.
   b. Another sublist item.
3. So there you are.
:::

Notice that the left pane shows the source *verbatim* — the `:span[…]{.goldenrod}`
directive, the `/cool/` italics shorthand, and the raw `$\alpha + \beta$` math are
displayed as you typed them — while the right pane shows them resolved into a
coloured span, italic text, and typeset mathematics. That contrast is the whole
value of the directive: the reader sees both the cause and the effect at once.

## What the directive emits

`markdown-demo` renders to a single grid container with four children — two
labels and two panes. Knowing the structure helps if you want to restyle the
demos for your own site:

```html
<div class='markdown-demo-container'>
  <div class='markdown-demo-code-label'>Markdown code</div>
  <div class='markdown-demo-output-label'>Markdown output</div>
  <div class='markdown-demo-markdown'>
    <pre><code class='hljs language-markdown'>…highlighted source…</code></pre>
  </div>
  <div class='markdown-demo-parsed'>
    …rendered output…
  </div>
</div>
```

The container is laid out as a two-column CSS grid (`grid-template-columns: 1fr
1fr`), so the source and output sit side by side on a wide screen. The two label
divs carry the headings *Markdown code* and *Markdown output*; the source lives in
`markdown-demo-markdown`, the rendered result in `markdown-demo-parsed`. JMarkdown
ships default styling for all of these classes, so demos look reasonable out of
the box, and you can override any of it in your own stylesheet.

| Class | Holds |
|---|---|
| `markdown-demo-container` | the whole grid |
| `markdown-demo-code-label` | the *Markdown code* heading (left) |
| `markdown-demo-output-label` | the *Markdown output* heading (right) |
| `markdown-demo-markdown` | the highlighted source (left pane) |
| `markdown-demo-parsed` | the rendered output (right pane) |

## How the two panes are produced

The left and right panes come from the *same* source text by two different
routes, and the difference matters for a couple of edge cases below.

The **right pane** is parsed normally: JMarkdown runs the directive body through
its full lexer and renderer, so every JMarkdown feature works inside a demo —
inline directives, math, footnotes, custom elements, scripts, and even other
container directives (with the colon-count caveat described under
[Nesting](#nesting-demos-around-other-directives)).

The **left pane** is *not* parsed as Markdown. The body is handed straight to
[highlight.js](https://highlightjs.org/) and displayed verbatim. This is
deliberate: if the example you are demonstrating contains a fenced code block, or
any other syntax that the lexer would try to consume, feeding it through the
parser a second time just to colour it would corrupt it. By syntax-highlighting
the raw text instead, the left pane can show *anything* — including fenced code,
raw HTML, or a half-finished snippet — without risk.

One small consequence of the verbatim handling: the directive strips a single
leading blank line from the source before highlighting, so the left pane is not
pushed down by the newline that naturally follows the opening fence. You do not
need to do anything for this; it just keeps the panel tidy.

## Choosing the highlight language: `{type=...}`

By default the left pane is highlighted as **Markdown**, which is right for the
overwhelming majority of demos. When the example you are showing is *not*
Markdown — most often raw HTML or a script — pass a `type` attribute on the
opening fence to tell highlight.js what language the source is in:

```markdown
:::markdown-demo{type=html}
<button onclick="alert('hi')">Press me</button>
:::
```

Because that source contains raw HTML, the `{type=html}` variant highlights it as
HTML (and, just as importantly, keeps highlight.js from misreading the angle
brackets as Markdown). Here is the result:

:::markdown-demo{type=html}
<button onclick="alert('hi')">Press me</button>
:::

The right pane is rendered the same way regardless of `type` — the attribute only
controls how the *source* is coloured on the left. The value is passed straight to
highlight.js as the language name, so any language highlight.js knows is valid:
`html`, `js`, `css`, `xml`, `latex`, `json`, and so on. If you omit `type`, the
language is `markdown`.

A reliable rule of thumb: **if the demo's source contains a literal HTML tag or a
script element, reach for `{type=html}`.** A demo that embeds a jmarkdown script
block (a script element whose `data-type` is `jmarkdown`) is the canonical case —
the surrounding panels throughout [Inline scripts](inline-scripts.html) and
[Block environments](block-environments.html) all use the `{type=html}` variant
for exactly this reason.

## Nesting demos around other directives

A `markdown-demo` is itself a container directive, delimited by colon fences. That
creates one wrinkle you must know about: **if the example you are demonstrating is
itself a container directive, the demo's fence must use *more* colons than the
inner one.** This is the ordinary colon-counting rule for nesting container
directives — the closing fence is matched by colon count, so an inner three-colon
closer would otherwise close the demo prematurely and fold the rest of your
document into the panel.

So to demonstrate a three-colon directive, wrap it in a *four*-colon demo (the
example below shows a strategic-form game, a three-colon directive in its own
right):

```markdown
::::markdown-demo
:::game
         Rock   & Paper  & Scissors
Rock     & (0,0)  & (-1,1) & (1,-1)
Paper    & (1,-1) & (0,0)  & (-1,1)
Scissors & (-1,1) & (1,-1) & (0,0)

row: Player 1
column: Player 2
caption: Rock-Paper-Scissors
:::
::::
```

The four-colon opening fence wraps the three-colon game directive cleanly:

::::markdown-demo
:::game
         Rock   & Paper  & Scissors
Rock     & (0,0)  & (-1,1) & (1,-1)
Paper    & (1,-1) & (0,0)  & (-1,1)
Scissors & (-1,1) & (1,-1) & (0,0)

row: Player 1
column: Player 2
caption: Rock-Paper-Scissors
:::
::::

If the inner example itself contains nested containers, bump the demo's count
further still — five colons wrapping a four-colon example, and so on. JMarkdown
registers `markdown-demo` at every fence width from three up to eight colons, so
you have plenty of room to nest. The general principle: **the outermost fence
always has the highest colon count.**

The same rule applies in the other direction. To show *how a `markdown-demo`
fence itself looks* — as the very first example on this page does — put the
literal opening fence inside a fenced code block (triple backticks), not inside
another demo. A code fence does not interpret directives, so the colons are shown
literally with nothing to count.

## A worked HTML example

Putting the pieces together, here is a demo whose source is a small block of raw
HTML. It needs `{type=html}` so the left pane is highlighted correctly, and it
shows a feature — a definition-style layout built from raw markup — that the right
pane renders live:

:::markdown-demo{type=html}
<dl>
  <dt>markdown-demo</dt>
  <dd>A container directive that shows source and output side by side.</dd>
  <dt>type</dt>
  <dd>An attribute selecting the highlight language for the left pane.</dd>
</dl>
:::

## Reference

### Syntax

```
:::markdown-demo[{type=LANG}]
…the example source…
:::
```

| Part | Meaning |
|---|---|
| opening fence | three (or more) colons followed by `markdown-demo`; use more colons when wrapping a container directive |
| `{type=LANG}` | optional; the highlight.js language for the **left** pane (default `markdown`) |
| body | the example, shown verbatim on the left and rendered on the right |
| closing fence | the bare colon fence, alone on its own line, with the matching colon count |

### Attributes

| Attribute | Default | Effect |
|---|---|---|
| `type` | `markdown` | Language name passed to highlight.js for the source (left) pane only. Does not affect rendering. |

### Behaviour at a glance

- **Left pane** — the source, syntax-highlighted by highlight.js, never re-parsed
  as Markdown. Safe for fenced code, raw HTML, and partial snippets.
- **Right pane** — the source parsed and rendered by JMarkdown's full pipeline.
  Every JMarkdown feature works inside it.
- **One source** — both panes derive from the same text, so a demo and its output
  can never disagree.
- **HTML only** — `markdown-demo` is a documentation aid for the web. It is
  registered on the HTML parser, so it has no effect in LaTeX output; author your
  print material without it.

### Gotchas

- **Colon counting.** Wrapping a container directive in a demo requires a higher
  colon count on the demo than on the inner directive (four around a three-colon
  directive, and so on). A missing or mismatched closing fence folds the rest of
  the document into the panel.
- **Closing fence alone on its line.** As with any container directive, the
  closing colon fence must be the only thing on its line.
- **Use `{type=html}` for HTML and scripts.** Without it, highlight.js highlights
  raw HTML or a script element as Markdown, which looks wrong and can mangle the
  display of angle brackets.
- **Showing the demo syntax itself.** To document the `markdown-demo` fence
  literally, put it in a fenced code block, not inside another demo.

